{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #695: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let $p_1<p_2<\\cdots$ be a sequence of primes such that $p_{i+1}\\equiv 1\\pmod{p_i}$. Is it true that\\[\\lim_k p_k^{1/k}=\\infty?\\]Does there exist such a sequence with\\[p_k \\leq \\exp(k(\\log k)^{1+o(1)})?\\] Current best: If we take the obvious 'greedy' chain with $2=p_1$ and $p_{i+1}$ is the smallest prime $\\equiv 1\\pmod{p_i}$ then Linnik's theorem implies that this sequence grows like\\[p_k \\leq e^{e^{O(k)}}.\\]It is conjectured that, for any prime $p$, there is a prime $p'\\leq p(\\log p)^{O(1)}$ which is congruent to $1\\pmod{p}$, which would imply this sequence grows like\\[p_k\\leq \\exp(k(\\log k)^{1+o(1)}).\\]An extensive study of the growth of finite prime chains was carried out by Ford, Konyagin, and Luca \\cite{FKL10}. Prize: no. OEIS: A061092. Tags: number theory.","id":"vf_2913b5b453983036","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos695.erdos_695 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos695.erdos_695.","id":"vf_653ffd4cf632b034","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/695.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_2913b5b453983036","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"erdos:695","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_653ffd4cf632b034","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"erdos:695","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepte